Main Idea Introduction

What is Art in bar?

ArtInBar is a application which started how university project, at SEPP(Software Engineering & Profesional Practtise), in this subject we have to develop a software from the idea to MVP deploy.

The idea lie in getting establishments that want to hold events and artists who want to perform in touch.

Core ideas

Our MVP

  • Registry for both types of users, venues and artists.
  • Profiles, with multiple attributes and a multimedia gallery.
  • A system of offers made by the venues, in order to let the artists know in what they are interested for concrete dates.
  • An instant messaging system that enables artists and venues to chat with each other and discuss any potential contracts.
  • A payment system, Paypal, that will help our users organizing their payments and provide us with financing.
  • Public announcements for every contract confirmed in our application by a payment. This provides our registered users with an added value.

Domain model

Payments

Payment development

Our current Paypal payment flow looks like this:

  1. User 1 wants to make a payment to User 2.
  2. User 1 fills the performance creation form and proceeds to pay through Paypal's Express Checkout API.
  3. User 1 pays the desired amount, plus Paypal's fee and our fee.
  4. We (currently payments@artinbar.com) receive the payment and keep our fee. The payment is stored in database.
  5. We make a payment to User 2 through Paypal's Payouts API for the original amount.
  6. We save the new payment and the performance in database.

For info on the API check the official Paypal documentation here: https://developer.paypal.com/docs/

The payment credentials for the demo account are:

  • artist1@artinbar.com - Mock account for an artist
  • venue@artinbar.com - Mock account for a venue
  • payments@artinbar.com - Mock account for us to keep the fee and forward the payment to the receiver.

The password for all three accounts is "artinbar"

Competitors

The main competitor we have found is called Gigstarter.

"Gigstarter is a platform which is focused on music. It facilitates a direct hiring between musicians and applicants who want to hire them. It is not an intermediary, they create a transparent market for the hiring of live music for the general public and offer the opportunity to the musicians to present themselves."

The research carried out was:

  • If you are an musician, you can only create a profile to promote yourself.
  • If you are an applicant, you can hire an musician. If you know no one, you can use the search engine to find them.
  • It has an agenda with upcoming concerts or events with live music.
  • The musicians can pay a fee to improve their profile to a PRO version. Basically, their business is based on earn money with these versions. There are actually 3 versions:
    • Basic or free: Access to your profile, evaluations about you as an artist, your concerts on your profile, notifications to your email and an online chat to chat with applicants.
    • PRO (paying 9.99/month): Put your profile more visible, you can put videos or photos on it, promote of your concerts, contact information and so on.
    • PRO+ (paying 14.95/month): Improve your PRO profile to an international way, opportunity of tours, you can create a profile to your manager or agency, support consultory and others.

There are others competitors we have to deal with:

  • Miuseek is a social networking service for musicians where they can create their band, find others musicians, create or seek upcoming events or concerts, hiring rehearsal places, contact with recording studios and so on.
  • La Factoria del Show is a company who helps you to prepare the best event you can do. You can hire bands or artists making contact with them, places, security, catering companies, etc.
  • Bandsintown Concerts is an android app where you can find the upcoming concerts or events on your city with a personal schedule.

Surveys conclusions

Performers Surveys

We've surveyed 27 differents performers mostly from Sevilla and Cceres, they are core into our project and we needed know about their preferences and difficulties when they are looking for establishments.

  • How hard is usually to find an establishment?: most performers, around 80%, find it moderately difficult or complicated.

  • How do you find an establishment?: That question has been really interesting because 80% of surveyed performers use internet or recommendations, while only 20% do it moving down the street.

  • How do you show your content to a new establishment?: Only 8% use a live performance to show their content, making easier to us be in line with artists methodologies.

  • Do you know other platforms like ours?: Only 20% of performers knew about others platforms and 10% didn't use them.

Users Surveys

We've surveyed 110 differents potential users between 18-65 years old, with a majority of interest on small artist that happend in their city. They are our target because they are going to be an incentive for establishment that want to increase their ganancies using our platform.

  • Do you have difficulties finding out about small events and exhibitions that you might be interested in attending?: 75% of surveyed potential users have difficulties finding events and exhibitions, that is what our platform is interested into resolve making public future events made by us.

  • How do you usually find out about the events of the small artists you attend?: 50% of surveyed use social networks or internet and 50% by word of mouth or posters on street, that because we want to unify those into our platform.

  • Do you know and have used applications that notify you of events in bars and venues in your city?: Only around 30% knew about them, and 15% never use them.

Establishment Surveys

The establishments are essential in our application since they are the ones that will give reasons to use us performers and normal users. That why we have surveyed them asking for their usual been when their are looking for a performer.

  • Why do you usually look for artists for your establishment?: Surveyed establishments tend to hire performers to attract a large clientele while none use ticket sales.

  • What means do you use to get in touch with new artists?: 50% use social networks to contact performers, and 35% use whatsapp, that our risk because they could bypass us but also that why we are looking for promote their events into our site.

  • Do you often look for new artists for your establishment, or repeat with artists you already know?: 70% of establishments are more often looking for new performers, and those are our principal targets, because them will find on us much easier to do that.

  • Would you be willing to pay a fee in relation to the contract with the artist in exchange for the comfort that the platform would give?: 90% of the establishments would be willing to pay a commission for the proposed services.

  • Are you aware of the existence of pages that provide a similar service?: 25% of them know about them.

Marketing Plan

Target Groups:

Our Marketing Plan is defined by three groups of people.

  • Artist:

This group is defined by people between 18 and 28 years old with interests in art and music, Also they like lives performances, pubs, night clubs, music concerts and music festivals.Who use smartphone and/or tablets. since the "Young" people are more accustomed to using technology and they are also the ones that are beginning in the artistic world, so they will be more interested on our platform.

  • Venue's Owner:

This group is defined as being people, aged between 30 and 65 years, who works on restoration,art and entertainment. They also are interested on live performance, pubs, night clubs and music festivals. they have to use smartphone and/or tablets and need people to perform a show at their pub/night club.

  • Investors:

This group is defined by people looking for a new project to invest in it

Contact Point:

we will reach the first two groups through advertisements on Facebook, Instagram, Messenger and Banners.

With a cost of 5.000 for artists we will reach from 12.900 to 57.000 clicks to web in a year.Also we will reach from 1.560.000 views to 5.700.000 views in a year.

with a cost of 5.000 for venue's owners we will reach from 8.700 to 45.000 clicks to web in a year. Also we will reach from 810.000 views to 3.000.000 views in a year.

Also has to reach investors, we will make a live presentation to them after finish the pilot project. Also we will email them

Work methodology

Slack

To have better comunications between different works groups we need next channels on Slack to speak to a especific groups or a specific topic:

  • Managers
  • Frontend
  • Backend
  • Meetings
  • Marketing
  • Off-Topics Also we can create more channels if we think it is necessary

GitFlow

To better work flow we will use a reduced GitFlow with the next branches:

  • master: only for stables version.
  • develop: only for version in development, when the version is finished, this branch will be merged with Master.
  • feature-[FeatureName]: you have to create a branch from develop with this format to develop a feature, when it is finished, this branch will be merged with develop.
  • hotfix-[HotFixName]: when you have to do a hotfix, you have to create a branch from master and when you finish the hotfix, you will merge this branch with master.

Commits

You have to do a commit for each work block or when going stop work, the title of the commit always have to start with one of the followings heads (including ":"):

  • Feat: when you have worked on a feature.
  • Doc: when you have worked on documentation.
  • Fix: when you have worked on a fast fix that isn't a feature.
  • HotFix: when you have worked on a Hot-Fix.

After the head you have to explain what you have done on one line and use the body to explain troubles or special topics and reference the issue of you work. (Ex. of reference: " refences #[number of issue] " )

If the commit closes the issue then you have to use " close #[number of issue] " or " resolve #[number of issue] "

Merging

After finish your work, you have to merge your branch with develop and delete your branch, the commands would be:

$ git checkout master

$ git merge yourBranch

$ git branch -d yourBrach

Scrum

We work with a reduced scrum, when we start a sprint we have to do a planning meeting, in this meeting we decide what we are going to do in this sprint, throughout the sprint we have a weekly meeting to explain our work during the week. Between weekly meetings we talk to each other with Slack and in small groups. At the end of the sprint we have to do a review and a retrospective meeting, it can be in the same meeting, but it has to be a different mind, we can not talk about revision and retrospective things at the same time.

summary of sprint

  • Planning meeting
  • X numbers of weekly meetings
  • review and retrospective meeting

Issues

A issue is a definition work for a person, only for a one person, this person can ask for help, but if the work have to be started for two persons. this issue is really two issues. A issue have two labels, this labels is for category and priority:

Categories:

  • Backend
  • Frontend
  • Documentation
  • Organization

    Priority:

  • P1-Now
  • P2-Very Important
  • P3-Mandatory
  • P4-Nice to have

Also is very important define when is closed a issue but it depends the category:

  • back/front end: a issue is closed when the feature/fix have been tested.
  • Documentation: another person who was not the author should review the document.
  • Organization: it don't have a clear definition.

Kanban Board

The Issues are organized on Kanban board, it have three columns:

  • To do: the issues start in this columns.
  • In Progress: When someone start to work on issue, it have to be placed on this column
  • Done: when a issue is closed, it have to be placed on this column

Punishment System

Punishment System

We have define a Warning methodology.

What is a Warning?

A Warning can implies two things:

while we are working at SEEP, a Warning means losing one point of the mark which will be shared between the others members of the team. After the subject, a Warning won't mean nothing, but if you reach 3 Warnings you will be fired.

Also you can be fired if whole the team agrees.

How get a Warning?

Anyone can say that other deserve a Warning because he haven't worked or has affect negatively to the project along this sprint and call for vote, if the half plus one of the team say 'yes', the person get a Warning. A person only can get one Warning for sprint, the vote have to be done at review-retrospective meeting.

How to lose a Warning?

If you work correctly along 3 sprints, you will lose a Advice if you have any.

Productivity metric systems

We have 3 metrics of productivity systems depending on speaker, project manager or developer roles.

Developer role

Developer productivity is related with the number of history points (HP) they has realised on time. Actually, a developer can do less HP than the PM has assigned to them if he is working less than expected or them could do more HP than the PM assigned to them if they helped in a task they was not assigned or has complete a task that was for the next week instead of current week.

We use then (HP accomplished on time)/(HP assigned for this time).

As a task could be miscalculated by the PM, we agree in a meeting if those tasks that was not accomplished on time were because the developer didn't work or the PM failed. In the second case, this task doesn't count.

Expected values are between 0.5 and 1.5, being 1 the ideal value, less than 0,7 bad values and more than 1 very good values. In case than all tasks of a developer were miscalculations, the productivity is 0/0, so we have no information this week about this developer. We will use then last week productivity for him.

Project manager role

The productivity of the project manager is voted by the developers. They should vote between 0 and 10, depending on task they had assigned had a good approximation in HP with the real time they worked (1 HP half an hour).

Speaker role

The productivity of the speaker is voted by his public. They should vote between 0 and 10, depending on how interesting and informative was the presentation.

Speaker and PM roles have different productivity scale than developers. As we want anonymize productivity, we should convert to the same scale.

We are using this:

  • From 0 to 5 -> lineal from 0 to 0.4
  • From 5 to 8 -> lineal from 0.4 to 1
  • From 8 to 10 -> lineal from 1 to 1.5

For example, a 4 is 0.32, a 7.4 is 0.88, and a 8.5 is 1.125.

First sprint

First sprint should aboard most important features so piloting users can give us feedback about them.

We are developing at this sprint:

  • Conceptual and domain models.
  • Home page with a master page.
  • Profiles pages for both actors.
  • Offer creation
  • Chat

As well as those features we are implementing it's design, that is mobile first.

Second sprint

Along the second sprint we are developing next features, improving some posible bugs that we could find and meeting piloting users so they can give us feedback:

  • Register for both actors.
  • Profile editing for both actos.
  • Payment gateway.
  • Deployment.

Third sprint

Along the third sprint we are developing next features, as well as we are including feature that we obtained from piloting users:

  • Public announcements
  • List of both artists
  • Delete offers
  • Terms of use and conditions page
  • Feedback gateway

Some features we would like to deal with are ssl security implementation and filters of announcements, but that was not inside of our MVP and we are only doing them if there is enough time.

Piloting Plan

Piloting Plan

Piloting project

The piloting project only will have the core of Art in Bar:

  • Login
  • View profiles
  • Chat with other users (the others users to chat will be part of the staff conected to the app)
  • manage offers

Purpose

With this plan we want found:

  • possible errors in the usability of Art In Bar.
  • Check that users feel comfortable with interface.
  • Check if there is any factor that we have overlooked in the design of the application.

Pilot users

We have found 14 pilots user, 10 for Artist and 4 for Venues, they gave us a phone number or email to take part on this app's develop.

Process of Test

We will meet with different user groups in a room with computers. Users will have a list of tasks to do in the application.

While users are doing the test, some staff members will be in the room to help if someone gets stuck.

Metrics

The computers on the tests will have access to the pilot project and will have a recording software, OBS in this case. We will record all test and have animation for each click, At the end of each task, they should answer some questions about the task and if ther have been troubles doing it. At the end of the test they have to answer a survey about their general opinion.

  • Numbers of clicks for each task.
  • Observe if the users have some trouble to realize the tasks.
  • General opinion on the use of application.
